The Scenario

My friend in the neighboring town needs help with her lemonade stand. She offers me part of her stand in exchange for my assistance.

First, I ask her to:

  1. Get data about her neighborhood
  2. Compare her neighborhood to my neighborhood
  3. Generate scenarios that might happen that would impact our stands (baseball games, garage sales etc.)

The Example

  1. DECISION: Supply something new to this market
  • PRODUCT: Lemon Concentrate Cubes
  • GEOGRAPHY: One town over
  • CUSTOMERS: Soccer moms, little leaguers, business professionals en-route to work
  1. QUESTIONS:
  • How will the performance of the secondary stand affect the size and timing of Lemon Concentrate Cube orders?
  • How will the value of Lemon Concentrate Cubes affect the value of my stand?
  • How will the fact that the secondary stand uses Apple Pay impact my stand and overall earnings?
  1. DATA:
  • something to represent volatility and correlation
  • something to represent volatility
  • exchange rates

(non lemonade examples) - stock prices - oil prices - USD/EUR exchange rates

  1. Visualize this candy data with box plots and autocorrelation functions

  1. Look at persistence
# autocorrelation
acf(coredata(candy_return), 
    main = "Candy Daily Autocorrelogram", 
    lag.max = 20, ylab = "", xlab = "", col = "blue", ci.col = "red")

# partial autocorrelation
pacf(coredata(candy_return), 
     main = "Candy Daily Partial Autocorrelogram", 
     lag.max = 20, ylab = "", xlab = "", col = "blue", ci.col = "red")

NOTES:

  • Confidence intervals are the red dashed lines.
  • ACF at lag 6 means the correlation of current Brent returns with returns 6 trading days ago, including any correlations from trading day 1 through 6.
  • PACF is simpler: it is the raw correlation between day 0 and day 6. – ACF starts at lag 0 (today); – PACF starts at lag 1 (yesterday).

LEARNING THE HARD WAY

Stylized Facts of the Market

  • Financial stock, bond, commodity etc. have highly interdependent relationships
  • Volatility is rarely constant and often has a structure (mean reversion) and is often dependent on the past
  • Past shocks persist
  • Extreme events are likely to happen with other extreme events
  • Negative returns are more likely than positive returns (left skew)
